      Project description

      In this project we are to classify images of clothes using Feed Forward Neural Networks. In the first step we examine the dataset and apply some preprocessing including normalization on it. In the second step we implement Feed Forward Neural Network. The implementation contains classes of Dataloader, Activation Functions, Loss Function, Layer and Feed Forward Neural Network. In next step the Neural Network will be trained and test images will be classified. Then we discuss effects of the parameters. In last step reduction of dimensions of the data will be illustrated using a specific Neural Network.

      In this part we apply normalization on the datasets. The normalization will be done by dividing each pixle by 255. Because value of each pixle is between 0 and 255. <br>
      2
      3
      Advantages of Normailzation in This Problem:
      4
      5
      * By normalizing the dataset the mean value will be a small value (something between 0 and 1). This will speeds up the calculations in the Neural Network and help it converge faster.
      6
      7
      * Normalization convene the inputs in a comparable range. It will enhance the performance and reduce errors. In fact the Normalization make the inputs smooth.
      8
      9
      * Normalization is helpful to reduce the chance of vanishing gradient. It will allow us to train deeper networks.
      10
      11
      * Normalization become very important in case of some particular activation functions like Sigmoid. Because at high values, saturation is potential. In fact gradient get closer to 0. This will cause the network to result inconsistent answers.
      12
      13
      * Another advantage of Normalization is preventing the values from being overflowd. Overflow cause inconsistent results which is not proper.

      In this part we apply normalization on the datasets. The normalization will be done by dividing each pixle by 255. Because value of each pixle is between 0 and 255.

      Advantages of Normailzation in This Problem:

      • By normalizing the dataset the mean value will be a small value (something between 0 and 1). This will speeds up the calculations in the Neural Network and help it converge faster.

      • Normalization convene the inputs in a comparable range. It will enhance the performance and reduce errors. In fact the Normalization make the inputs smooth.

      • Normalization is helpful to reduce the chance of vanishing gradient. It will allow us to train deeper networks.

      • Normalization become very important in case of some particular activation functions like Sigmoid. Because at high values, saturation is potential. In fact gradient get closer to 0. This will cause the network to result inconsistent answers.

      • Another advantage of Normalization is preventing the values from being overflowd. Overflow cause inconsistent results which is not proper.

      By choosing low learning rates there is a good chance that the network do not miss local mins. In other words the training will be more reliable. <br>
      2
      In other view by choosing low learning rates steps of weight changes become tiny and traveling along different values become slower. This cause that the network need much more time to converge. <br><br>
      3
      4
      By choosing high learning rates there is a chance that the training will not converge. Steps of weight changes become so big that it may omit some local mins and cause the accuracy to reduce and the loss to increase. <br><br>

      • Sigmoid:
        In sigmoid function reaction of y values to the changes in x is very little. So the derivative values become very small and converge to 0. In other words there is a good chance for vanishing of gredient which is not proper. Because the network stops learning. In big neural networks Sigmoid and Tanh and tanh caused lots of neurons to be activated in the same way. And it requires an intensive calculation. This is the reason why we see that using Sigmoid or Tanh function makes learning of the network to take large amount of time.

      • Relu:
        Being non-linear makes Relu a good estimator. In addition it is possible to converge with various functions using combinations of Relu.
        By using Relu lots of values become zero. It speeds up the calculation. So load of calculation in Relu is much smaller than Sigmoid and Tanh. Because of that in deep neural networks Relu is prefered considerably in comparison with Sigmoid and Tanh.
        Disadvantage of Relu is possibility of vanishing grediant. By vanishing of grediant learning stops and we may get inconsistent results.

      • Leaky Relu:
        To solve problem of vanishing in Relu it is good to use Leaky Relu. Instead of being zero when the input is negative, Leaky ReLU will assume a slope value which prevent outputs to vanish.

      Batch: <br>

      The batch size represent number of samples which will be propagated in the neural network. It needs less memory. The reason is by training the network using fewer samples, the training process needs smaller memory. Using batches it is possible to achive good generalization. <br>
      4
      5
      As the batch size gets larger, loss decrease slower and the netwoek needs more epoches to converge and reach the minimum loss. Large batch size also speeds up each epoch. Because calculation of updated weights occur less often. <br>
      6
      7
      Training with low batch sizes lead the model to converge in flat minimums. In contrast large batch sizes converge to sharp minimums. Flat or sharp minimumes show generalization of convergence of the network. <br>
      8

      When we use batch size of 16 it takes more time to do each epoch but it needs less epoches to converge. We can see that accuracy in this case is good. It proves that convergence needs less epoches to happen (In comparison with batch size of 128). <br>

      When we use batch size of 128 it takes less time to do each epoch considerably. The accuracy is lower in comparison with batch size of 16 because when we use large batch sizes training needs more epochs to converge. <br>
      11

      Small batches causes the grediants to fluctuates much more in comparison with larger batches. It causes lower accuracy. And it is its disadvantage.

      Batch:

      The batch size represent number of samples which will be propagated in the neural network. It needs less memory. The reason is by training the network using fewer samples, the training process needs smaller memory. Using batches it is possible to achive good generalization.

      As the batch size gets larger, loss decrease slower and the netwoek needs more epoches to converge and reach the minimum loss. Large batch size also speeds up each epoch. Because calculation of updated weights occur less often.

      Training with low batch sizes lead the model to converge in flat minimums. In contrast large batch sizes converge to sharp minimums. Flat or sharp minimumes show generalization of convergence of the network.

      When we use batch size of 16 it takes more time to do each epoch but it needs less epoches to converge. We can see that accuracy in this case is good. It proves that convergence needs less epoches to happen (In comparison with batch size of 128).
      When we use batch size of 128 it takes less time to do each epoch considerably. The accuracy is lower in comparison with batch size of 16 because when we use large batch sizes training needs more epochs to converge.

      Small batches causes the grediants to fluctuates much more in comparison with larger batches. It causes lower accuracy. And it is its disadvantage.

      6

      Epoch:

      An epoch is a cycle which the training dataset passes through the network. By having proper number of epoches we can achive generalization in our network. In fact performance of the network become better on classifing unseen samples.

      To see overfitting in the network I choose 130 for number of epoches. As we can see in the diagram of loss for train and test dataset (Shown 2 cells after this cell), it seems that loss of test dataset begin to rise at epoch 24. But loss of train dataset decrease all the time. It seems that the network begin to overfit in epoch 24.
      In addition we can see in accuracy diagram that the accuracy of test data begin to fall in epoch 25.
      These things prove that at epoch 24 network begin to learn details of train data which are not necessary to classify an unseen sample. At epoch 24 generalization of network begin to weaken.
      To achive best performance on an unseen sample we should use early stopping and end learning of the network at epoch 24.
